Learning the words "triangle," "square," and "circle" are NOT the most important concepts for toddlers to learn.

YOU show your toddler how to try again and not give up.
YOU show your toddler how to successfully place the object where it is supposed to go! üèÜ

Of course, be sure to make appropriate noises and facial expressions as you demonstrate this basic, but very important, life lesson. üòÉüëè

shared_text:
The Gottman Institute
July 14 at 10:01 PM ¬∑

Feeling estranged from your own child is painful.

Research indicates the most important predictor of a child‚Äôs emotional and psychological stability is the closeness of the parent/child relationship. If your child is not opening up when they are upset, the relationship may not be as close as it needs to be. There are two habits that parents routinely engage in that shut down communication and drive a child away: negating feelings and mistaking sympathy for empathy.

In many cases, honoring your child‚Äôs feelings is all they need to feel better. Simply knowing their parent understands allows them to feel secure and forge ahead. Some sympathetic statements, on the other hand, disrupt any chance of emotional attunement, instead of helping them work through their difficult feelings.

Dr. Erin Leonard discusses how to be a parent your child wants to confide in on the Gottman Relationship Blog: https://bit.ly/2DHZe8u

K-12 parents: Lake Superior School District is working on designing a safe return to school in the fall. The district will be following CDC guidelines and mandates from the State of Minnesota.

This fall could be distance learning or a hybrid which would be a combination of in school and distance learning. We are also looking at how to assist our students and staff with their social emotional health during these stressful times.

We would like each family to fill out a survey geared toward your student. We have an elementary survey and a high school survey. We also have a student survey for students in grades 7-12 and will be sending that to their school email accounts. Please have your students check their email.

The surveys are available on the LSSD website and on the Parent Portal site. We will have paper forms available in the District Office and the WKS office. The parent surveys will also be included in your email.

Thank you in advance for filling out the surveys giving us more information as we plan for the upcoming school year.

***Tape Pull Activity***

This super simple and super fun activity targets so many important developmental skills.....another win for painter‚Äôs tape!!!

1. Visual Perception ‚Äî figuring out which piece of tape to pull off first

2. Fine Motor ‚Äî using the hand/finger muscles to peel the ends of the tape

3. Gross Motor ‚Äî doing the activity on a vertical surface to strengthen the neck and shoulder muscles

4. Crossing Midline ‚Äî By using one hand, the child is forced to cross the imaginary vertical line running down the middle of his body

June 29 at 10:41 PM ¬∑

***Tape Pull Activity***

This super simple and super fun activity targets so many important developmental skills.....another win for painter‚Äôs tape!!!

1. Visual Perception ‚Äî figuring out which piece of tape to pull off first

2. Fine Motor ‚Äî using the hand/finger muscles to peel the ends of the tape

3. Gross Motor ‚Äî doing the activity on a vertical surface to strengthen the neck and shoulder muscles

4. Crossing Midline ‚Äî By using one hand, the child is forced to cross the imaginary vertical line running down the middle of his body

shared_text:
Tots On Target
June 28 at 5:35 AM ¬∑

If you‚Äôre not exactly the most athletic person like me (no, it is NOT a prerequisite for PTs to be good at sports), you might find practicing ball skills on the bottom of your priority list.
.
.
However, these skills actually target many others like visual tracking, balance, directionality, timing and response times, depth perception, and upper/lower extremity coordination.
.
.
Well, there‚Äôs no need to panic over ball practice-this activity is so easy to set up and targets all those important skills!
.
.
To advance this activity try one of these:
1. Time the child and then encourage him to beat his score.
2. Have tap the balloon with only one hand and place the other hand behind his back.
3. Have him balance on one leg as he throws the balloon and catches it.

Attention Families!
Those who received free and reduced meals during the 2019-2020 school year are eligible for summer assistance called P-EBT. It is a pandemic assistance program that is a one time benefit of $325 per child for help during this summer. You must apply between June 8th and June 12th by noon. You will receive a card to use in the mail that is loaded with your benefit amount for your household. If you receive EBT already, you will receive your benefits on your current card. Please take advantage of this program as we are not providing lunches this summer.

post_text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sqqEG6mMuqw&feature=youtu.be&utm_source=ActiveCampaign&utm_medium=email&utm_content=Llama%20Llama%20Red%20Pajama%20Story%20and%20Book%20Activities&utm_campaign=Llama%20Llama%20Red%20Pajama%20Book%20Activities
Ideas to extend the story:
Have everyone cuddle up in their pajamas for some extra read-aloud time.
Head to the kitchen sink and find a variety of objects to experiment with to see which ones float and which ones sink.
Go on a red hunt through the house. How many things can your child find that are read?
Let your child call a loved one on the phone to visit.
Practice running in the yard.
Make a pillow fort for all your stuffed animals.

Governor Walz has announced that the Distance Learning Period will extend for the rest of the 2019-20 school year.

The Lake Superior School District will continue to provide meals along with school material drop off and pick ups as we have been doing. This will continue for the remainder of the school year.

We will keep everyone updated once we have a revised school calendar with an end date and other information as it is available.

post_text: AEOA partner Minnesota After-school Advance has a program in place to help families purchase Chromebooks at a discount. More information can be found below:
shared_text:
Arrowhead Economic Opportunity Agency
April 21 at 3:48 PM ¬∑

Another opportunity from an AEOA community partner. See their website for more information.

Minnesota Afterschool Advance program has temporarily pivoted from focusing on using the K-12 Education Tax Credit to help pay for out-of-school time activities to getting Chromebooks to families at 75% off to aid with distance learning.

Plus, Youthprise is providing scholarships to families for the remaining 25% while funding remains, so most families are able to get a Chromebook for no out-of-pocket cost through the program.

Lake Superior School District # 381 - Two Harbors, MN
April 7 at 7:47 PM ¬∑

April 7, 2020

Dear Families,

The Minnesota Department of Health (MDH), in partnership with the Minnesota Department of Education, continues to fine tune the definitions that guide the childcare services we provide families. Current guidance is that we can provide childcare for Tier 1 and Tier 2 workers in the event that both parents/caregivers are working out of the home. This includes children 5 years (kindergarten) through 12 years of age who are enrolled in our district and would normally attend classes during this time. If a parent/caregiver is in the home, best practice is to keep children home. In this way, we can follow MDH ratio requirements and provide the safest and healthiest environment possible for our children and staff. According to the MDH, ‚ÄúThe care for children of these workers is intended for extreme circumstances in which no parent or guardian is available to care for a child due to employment as a critical worker.‚Äù
Thank you for following this guidance during these uncertain times.

Dr. William Crandall
Superintendent

shared_text:
Lake Superior School District # 381 - Two Harbors, MN
April 1 at 12:47 PM ¬∑

The School Board of LSSD approved a revised school calendar.

These are important changes due to the Stay Home MN order from Governor Walz. During the time of distance learning, only during the time of distance learning, we will operate under a 5 day school week.

We will also continue to educate our students next week, which should have been our spring break. We will start this immediately, with this Friday, being an education day.

When we receive notice from the Governor that we can return to school, we will go back to our regular calendar, with a revised end date.

March 31 at 7:48 PM ¬∑

Calling all Junior Rangers! This Wednesday, April 1st at 12:00 pm PDT, join us as Mount Rainier National Park and the Washington National Parks Fund go on a virtual field trip to explore what it would be like to be a park ranger.

This 30 min field trip is perfect for kids PreK-3rd grade or the young at heart. Education Ranger Annie will read the book If I Were a Park Ranger by Catherine Stier. The book features a diverse cast of children who talk about all of the things they could do if they were a park ranger. After reading the book, Ranger Annie and Ranger Julie will hold a Q&A about what it‚Äôs like to be a park ranger at Mount Rainier National Park.

Follow the link to sign up. https://zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_Bdm2lWjKR4OM9IX3fo9ioA

___
NPS Photo of ranger in a tent reading to two kids. ~jg/kl

post_text: Balance!
shared_text:
Mrs Speechie P
March 22 at 12:14 AM ¬∑

Solitary play IS an important type of play - but should not be the only type of play a child engages in. This is important for parents to know because 1. We should not be entertaining or playing/working with our kids at all times, and also 2. We should be playing with our kids SOME of the time. I will also add that this is a very complicated time and many families have many more important things to take care of at the moment like rent and food. The amount of time we play with our kids WILL and SHOULD be dependent on our circumstances- so please do not feel guilty if this is not a priority. Hugs and take care all ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è

drbeckyathome
March 13 at 2:26 PM ¬∑

Not much is as hard as sitting with uncertainty. And we are in a time right now of extreme uncertainty and worry.

There's not one big thing to do in moments like these, but rather lots of little things to help manage our anxiety and reduce the impact of our anxiety on the others around us.

Remember: also contagious is your mindset about the coronavirus, and we want to protect our kids from doomsday thinking and panic spirals.

So, here's a list of ideas, to manage our own anxiety and to help our kids make sense of what's happening around them.

Go to www.drbeckyathome.com for a full article and to see these tips in one place.

#psychology #momentsinmotherhood #parenting #parentingtips #parentingsupport #healthanxiety #communication #emotionalintelligence #family #momlife #anxiety #consciousparenting #respectfulparenting #mindfulparenting #coronavirus

‚ú®Balance (vestibular sense)‚Å†‚†Ä
‚ú®Neck & back muscles‚Å†‚†Ä
‚ú®Visual tracking‚Å†‚†Ä
‚ú®Arm & wrist strength‚Å†‚†Ä
‚ú®Core strength‚Å†‚†Ä
‚ú®Flexor muscles‚Å†‚†Ä
‚ú®Spinal strength‚Å†‚†Ä
‚ú®Familiarity with gravity‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Mommy Academy goes into this in detail in Remarkable Infants with lots of tips on how to bring in more play to make this a more enjoyable experience for your little one. ‚Å†

Soooo does your little one like tummy time?? Did you discover any tricks that made it a more enjoyable experience for you little one? DO TELL!

5 Tips to Get Your Toddler to Eat Healthier Foods {Recipe Included!}

Duluth Mom
February 24 at 12:31 PM ¬∑

"I have tried every trick in the book to get my toddler to eat nutritious foods and, over the last year, I have narrowed it down to five tricks that have worked best in our house. These are not scientific tips written by a nutrition expert, just ideas from a frustrated mother who has needed to get crafty in order to get her child to eat something other than bagged chicken shaped like dinosaurs."

post_text:
We hope you are healthy. If not here are some guidelines when to stay home. Children should not attend class if they are ill or exhibit symptoms of an oncoming illness.
This includes:
*A fever of 100 degrees or more within the last 24 hours
*Diarrhea/vomiting-keep your child home for 24 hours after the last episode
*A sore throat
*An earache
*Red eyes or discharge from the eyes
*Yellow or greenish discharge from the nose
*Harsh cough
*Chills

shared_text:
Milestones & Miracles
November 22, 2019 at 11:09 AM ¬∑

I work with some brilliant parents.They often share ideas and strategies with me that are worth passing on, like this one...
When her toddler began melting down in the store (this) mom grabbed the umbrella from her purse just to serve as a distraction to the toddler long enough for her to quickly wrap up her shopping. What happened next was surprising and magical! The toddler settled in under the safety of the umbrella which dampened the overwhelming noise of the store, shaded her from the bright fluorescent lights above and reduced the visual stimuli around her. Her meltdown ceased! Mom reported she didn't have to rush, her daughter felt safe under her polka dot canopy and mom was able to finish her shopping without another scream or tear. GENIUS!!

YOU show your toddler how to take the circle piece and mistakenly try to put it in the triangle spot.
YOU show your toddler how to try again and not give up.
YOU show your toddler how to successfully place the object where it is supposed to go! üèÜ

Of course, be sure to make appropriate noises and facial expressions as you demonstrate this basic, but very important, life lesson. üòÉüëè

shared_text:
Play Move Improve
September 3, 2019 at 3:49 AM ¬∑

Skipping is a gross motor skill that I encourage children to learn, because it incorporates balance, core strength, timing, rhythm, and spatial awareness.

Set up 5 strips of masking tape and teach children to hop on the spot with their right foot, then step on the next strip of tape with their left foot... hop on the spot with their left foot, then step forward to the next strip of tape with their right foot, etc.

To learn more, order my book bundle that explains gross motor development and skipping activities for children.
